    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n               <jats:p>We examine empirically and theoretically the relation between firms\u2019 risk and distance to consumers in a production network. We document two novel facts: firms farther away from consumers have higher risk premiums and higher exposure to aggregate productivity. We quantitatively explain these findings using a general equilibrium model featuring a multilayer production process. The economic force is \u201cvertical creative destruction,\u201d that is, positive productivity shocks to suppliers devalue customers\u2019 assets-in-place, thereby lowering the cyclicality of downstream firms\u2019 values. We show that vertical creative destruction varies with competition and firm characteristics and generates sizable cross-sectional differences in risk premiums.</jats:p>",
